  "prompt": "Cost for 1kg of A is 260 USD and 1kg of B is 380. AB is made by mixing A and B. If 1kg of AB costs 300, what was the ratio that A and B has mixed?",
  "response": "Let's solve the problem using a weighted average approach. Let the ratio of A to B be \\( x:y \\).\n\nThe cost per kg of A is $260, and the cost per kg of B is $380. Since 1 kg of the mixture AB costs $300, we have the equation:\n\n\\[\n260x + 380y = 300(x + y)\n\\]\n\nExpanding the right side gives:\n\n\\[\n260x + 380y = 300x + 300y\n\\]\n\nRearrange terms to get:\n\n\\[\n380y - 300y = 300x - 260x\n\\]\n\nSimplifying gives:\n\n\\[\n80y = 40x\n\\]\n\nDivide both sides by 40:\n\n\\[\n2y = x\n\\]\n\nSo, the ratio \\( x:y \\) is \\( 2:1 \\). This means A and B were mixed in the ratio 2:1.",
